A-L-B, N-L-B, and G-W-L-B: picking the load balancer.

The A-L-B terminates the H-T-T-P connection, parses the request, and routes on its content. Its object model starts with a listener, which is a port and protocol. The listener holds rules, evaluated in priority order. Each rule has conditions, like path, host, header, query string, source I-P, or H-T-T-P method, and an action, like forward, weighted forward, redirect, fixed response, or authenticate. The action points at a target group, whose targets can be an instance, an I-P for on-prem or peered targets, or a Lambda function. The A-L-B is the default for web apps, A-P-Is, and microservices.

The N-L-B operates at Layer four. It moves packets rather than parsing them, which makes it fast and protocol-agnostic. It gives you a static I-P per availability zone, or an Elastic I-P; it preserves the client's real source I-P, whereas an A-L-B rewrites it using the X-Forwarded-For header; it handles millions of requests per second at single-digit-millisecond latency; and it's the only load-balancer type that supports U-D-P. Reach for N-L-B when you need a static I-P for firewall whitelisting, when the traffic isn't H-T-T-P, like gaming, I-o-T, or custom protocols, or when raw latency matters more than Layer-seven features.

The G-W-L-B is niche. It sits inline as a transparent bump-in-the-wire for a fleet of third-party appliances, using the GENEVE protocol on port six-zero-eight-one to encapsulate a packet, hand it to a firewall or intrusion-detection system, and deliver it onward. The workloads never know it's there. Recognise it when a design says "deploy third-party firewalls scalably and transparently."
